<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-70-0155 </DOCNO><TEXT>Computed tomography is regarded by many as a complicated union of sophisticatedx-ray equipment and computer technology. This book overcomes these complexities.The rigid technicalities of the machinery and the clinical aspects ofcomputed tomography are discussed including the preparation of patients,both physically and mentally, for scanning. Furthermore, the author alsoexplains how to set up and run a computed tomography department, includingadvice on how the room should be designed.</TEXT></DOC>